I   wrote yesterday about the US Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=
=99s theory of stock buybacks. In particular, there is sort of a background=
 theory of =E2=80=9Cbuybacks are bad because companies should be spending t=
hat money on salaries or research instead,=E2=80=9D but the SEC=E2=80=99s c=
oncern is the more niche theory that =E2=80=9Cbuybacks are bad because exec=
utives sell stock when companies are buying.=E2=80=9D I quoted a 2018 speec=
h by former SEC Commissioner Robert Jackson:
In half of the buybacks we studied, at least one executive sold shares in t=
he month following the buyback announcement. In fact, twice as many compani=
es have insiders selling in the eight days after a buyback announcement as =
sell on an ordinary day. So right after the company tells the market that t=
he stock is cheap, executives overwhelmingly decide to sell.
Like three people emailed me to say: Well, of course. Most of the time, com=
panies announce a buyback when they announce quarterly earnings. And most p=
ublic companies have =E2=80=9Cblackout periods,=E2=80=9D in which executive=
s are not allowed to trade stock for some portion of each quarter (when the=
y might have nonpublic information about earnings), but=C2=A0are=C2=A0allow=
ed to sell stock in the =E2=80=9Copen window=E2=80=9D shortly after the com=
pany announces earnings (because then all of the information is public). If=
 executives can only trade on 30 days each quarter, and those 30 days are t=
he ones right after an earnings announcement, then executives will naturall=
y concentrate their trading in the times after buyback announcements. But i=
t is not=C2=A0because of the buyback; it is because of how public-company c=
alendars work.
Anyway though the SEC does seem keen on this theory, and the new rules it a=
dopted yesterday include that each public company will have to disclose =E2=
=80=9Cany policies and procedures relating to purchases and sales of the is=
suer=E2=80=99s securities during a repurchase program by its officers and d=
irectors, including any restriction on such transactions.=E2=80=9D I pointe=
d out that this is a soft way for the SEC to say =E2=80=9Ccompanies=C2=A0sh=
ould=C2=A0restrict executives from trading stock during a buyback.=E2=80=9D
Combine that with the open-window point, and you get something like the fol=
lowing:
=09Executives can only trade in a short window after earnings.=09The SEC wa=
nts to ban them from trading during a stock buyback.=09If a company does a =
buyback, it=E2=80=99s going to be in the short window after earnings.
  [9]

=09Therefore, if a company does buybacks regularly, its executives will pre=
tty much never be able to trade stock.=09Therefore executives will have to =
stop selling stock, or companies will have to stop doing buybacks.

Feels like the sort of result the SEC might like.

