  [1] I am being very general here, and this description is accurate mainly=
 for held-to-maturity bonds and loans. Banks classify other bonds as availa=
ble-for-sale, and their market value is a bit more relevant for accounting =
and capital, though there is some controversy about  the details there.


  [2] In particular, I worked at Goldman Sachs Group Inc. during the global=
 financial crisis, including when Goldman became a bank holding company in =
2008. I recall that, before 2008, Goldman could be a bit snooty about the r=
egular banks: =E2=80=9CWe mark everything to market, which imposes discipli=
ne and makes us smart and careful,=E2=80=9D was the message, =E2=80=9Cwhile=
 regular banks can just say that their loans are =E2=80=98held to maturity=
=E2=80=99 and never reflect their true value in their financial statements.=
=E2=80=9D=20


  [3] I have cited it a few times now, but this 2021 Journal of Finance pap=
er by Itamar Drechsler, Alexi Savov and Philipp Schnabl, =E2=80=9CBanking o=
n Deposits: Maturity Transformation without Interest Rate Risk,=E2=80=9D is=
 a good modern explanation of this theory. A sample: =E2=80=9CWe show that =
despite having a large maturity mismatch banks do not take on significant i=
nterest rate risk. Rather, because of the deposit franchise, maturity trans=
formation actually reduces the amount of interest rate risk banks take on. =
Two essential properties of the deposit franchise drive this result. First,=
 the deposit franchise gives banks market power over retail deposits, which=
 allows them to borrow at rates that are both low and insensitive to market=
 interest rates. Second, while running a deposit franchise incurs high oper=
ating costs (branches, salaries, marketing, technology), these costs do not=
 vary much over time and hence are also insensitive to interest rates. Thus=
, even though deposits are short term, funding via a deposit franchise rese=
mbles funding with long-term fixed-rate debt."


  [4] Even Byrne Hobart, who shorted SVB and flagged its insolvency back in=
 February, didn=E2=80=99t really think it was a big deal: He wrote at the t=
ime that =E2=80=9Cone reason banks aren't required to mark assets to market=
 is that they can hold them indefinitely as long as they have deposits,=E2=
=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Cit would take an absolutely titanic bank run to ac=
tually impair the company=E2=80=99s liquidity, so a run is unlikely.=E2=80=
=9D=20


  [5] Here is Bloomberg News on the   proposed regulatory changes. Here is =
a column from  Bank Reg Blog. Here is  a Twitter thread from Dan Davies.


  [6] Here is one more that is so speculative that I am embarrassed and put=
ting it into a footnote: Last year=E2=80=99s collapse of a bunch of big lev=
ered crypto firms, and particularly FTX, put a distinct focus on the *balan=
ce-sheet* value of leveraged financial institutions, not their *franchise v=
alue*. Even at the end for FTX, as its balance sheet was   public and horri=
fying, Sam Bankman-Fried was out trying to raise money with the argument th=
at FTX=E2=80=99s franchise value =E2=80=94 its customer base, its reputatio=
n, its regulatory licenses =E2=80=94 was worth enough to fill the balance-s=
heet hole. That didn=E2=80=99t work at all, and a lot of people viewed it a=
s sort of insane and fraudulent, and the whole idea is tarnished now.


  [7] I think I get this idea, that banking is a relic of a pre-mark-to-mar=
ket world but that the world around it has changed, from my reading of Nich=
olas Dunbar=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CThe Devil=E2=80=99s Derivatives=E2=80=9D and=
 Friedman and Kraus=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CEngineering the Financial Crisis.=E2=
=80=9D


  [8] Also, on Theory 2, if the assets have lost value then the liabilities=
 have also become smaller: Your sticky core deposits, which still pay low i=
nterest rates, offset some of the asset losses. Part of the value that   JP=
Morgan Chase & Co. attributed to First Republic Bank was this =E2=80=9Ccore=
 deposit=E2=80=9D value.


  [9] This is loose. Companies can do buybacks using 10b5-1 plans or accele=
rated share repurchases where much or all of the purchasing happens during =
a blackout period, though they will *sign* those plans (and presumably anno=
unce them) during an open window.=20


