<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is going on? I think there are=C2=A0two w=
ays to think about the basic business of banking:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Banks borrow short to lend long. </em>They use deposits (which can be w=
ithdrawn at any time) to fund loans and buy bonds (which don=E2=80=99t get =
repaid for a long time).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Banks=C2=A0</em>really=C2=A0<em>borrow long to lend long</em>. They use=
 deposits to fund loans and buy bonds, and as a technical legal matter thos=
e deposits are short-term (and can be withdrawn at any time), but they aren=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>really</em>. Most people =E2=80=94=C2=A0and most busine=
sses =E2=80=94=C2=A0keep their money at a bank because it is convenient, it=
=E2=80=99s where their paycheck direct deposit and bill auto-pays are set u=
p, and it would be a pain to move to a new bank. Most people do not obsessi=
vely check the interest rates on their bank accounts to find the highest on=
e, or obsessively check the financial condition of their bank to see if it=
=E2=80=99s safe. Banks invest in customer <em>relationships</em> =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0by building branches and cross-selling services and offering convenie=
nces like online banking =E2=80=94=C2=A0and those relationships are long-te=
rm and sticky and include deposits. In a real economic sense, banks are mak=
ing loans and buying bonds that match the duration of their long-term, rela=
tionship-driven deposits.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Theory 1, banking is an inherently risky bu=
siness model (if the depositors all ask for their money back at once, you a=
re in trouble). Specifically, it is a model with a ton of interest-rate ris=
k.=C2=A0More specifically, if interest rates go=C2=A0<em>up</em>, that=E2=
=80=99s bad. You got all these short-term deposits and used them to buy lon=
g-term fixed-rate assets; when rates go up, your long-term assets lose valu=
e and you have to pay more interest on the short-term deposits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Theory 2, banking is less risky, and in par=
ticular it has less interest-rate risk. But also, the interest-rate risk=C2=
=A0<em>goes the other way</em>. If your model is =E2=80=9Cwe have all these=
 deposits that are locked up indefinitely, and we pay 0% interest on them, =
and we always will, and we use them to make loans and buy bonds,=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0then you want interest rates to go=C2=A0<em>up</em>. If interest rate=
s go up:=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You don=E2=80=99t pay any more interes=
t on your deposits: They are locked up forever at 0% interest, nobody check=
s their rate, nobody asks for more or moves their money.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your long-term fixed-rate assets (bonds, loans) lo=
se=C2=A0<em>market value</em>, but you don=E2=80=99t care. If you bought a =
3% bond when rates were 3%, and now rates are 5%, your bond is only worth, =
say, 85 cents on the dollar. If you sold it today, you=E2=80=99d have a 15%=
 loss. But you have no reason to sell it today: You bought it using long-te=
rm funding, so you just hold it to maturity, when it will pay off 100 cents=
 on the dollar. In the meantime, it will keep paying you 3% interest, which=
 is less than the market interest rate, but still a lot more than the 0% yo=
u are paying on deposits.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your net=
 interest=C2=A0<em>income=C2=A0</em>goes up. Some of your assets have float=
ing interest rates, so when rates go up they pay you more. Other assets hav=
e fixed interest rates, but some of them mature each day, and you take the =
money and use it to make new loans and buy new bonds with higher interest r=
ates. Your interest=C2=A0<em>expense=C2=A0</em>stays flat (because your dep=
ositors never withdraw their money or ask for higher interest), but your in=
terest income goes up, so you make more money.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think a crude way to put it is that Theory 1=
 is the sort of modern-finance, markets-oriented, mark-everything-to-market=
 approach. It is the way almost everybody in financial markets thinks about=
 almost everything: If you have funding that can be withdrawn at any time, =
that is short-term funding; if you buy long-term fixed-rate assets and inte=
rest rates go up, you have a mark-to-market loss, and that loss is in every=
 meaningful sense =E2=80=9Creal.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the crude way to put it would be that=
 Theory 2 is the traditional theory of=C2=A0<em>bankers.=C2=A0</em>Theory 2=
 is a sort of sociologically accurate description of how banking has actual=
ly worked in practice, most of the time, for the last few hundred years. Ba=
nks do not expect all their depositors to withdraw money on a moment=E2=80=
=99s notice, because they usually don=E2=80=99t. Banks do not worry too muc=
h about marking all of their assets to market, because they plan to hold th=
ose assets until they mature, and they usually do. Banks generally find tha=
t their net interest income is higher when interest rates are higher and lo=
wer when rates are lower, so they like higher interest rates.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am exaggerating the differences here to make=
 the contrast clearer. Of course no=C2=A0actual banker would say Theory 2 t=
he way I have said it; actual bankers seem to have some blend of Theory 1 a=
nd Theory 2. Every banker is aware of the risk of bank runs. Sometimes depo=
sitors do all ask for their money back at once, and that=E2=80=99s bad, and=
 banks and regulators think about that problem and do things to prevent and=
 mitigate it. Nobody says =E2=80=9Cinterest rates on deposits will be zero =
forever,=E2=80=9D but what they do is talk about a thing called =E2=80=9Cde=
posit beta,=E2=80=9D which means that when short-term interest rates go up =
by 1%, bank deposit rates go up by some fraction (the beta) of 1%: Bank dep=
ositors are=C2=A0<em>slow=C2=A0</em>to react to changing interest rates, fo=
r the reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0relationships, convenience, rational ignorance=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0that I talked about in Theory 2. Nobody says =E2=80=9Cthe m=
arket value of a bank=E2=80=99s assets doesn=E2=80=99t matter,=E2=80=9D but=
 banks generally=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>get to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/31378235.260432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTMvc3ZiLWNvdWxkbi10LWlnbm9yZS1pdHMtbG=
9zc2VzLWJ1dC10aGUtZmVkLWNhbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTA0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVka=
XVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MDQmdXRtX2NhbXBh=
aWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBed1c394d" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  ignore tha=
t market value</a> in their financial statements and in their capital accou=
nting,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0disclosing it only in a footnote near the back of the financials.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am tempted to say that Theory 1 is correct a=
nd Theory 2 is wrong, but that is just because I grew up in a modern-financ=
e, markets-oriented, mark-everything-to-market world.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But Theory 2 has a lot going for it, empirically; it probably giv=
es you a better sense of what banks are doing (building long-term relations=
hips, accumulating sticky deposits, investing them in a way that roughly ma=
tches their stickiness) than Theory 1 does.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> You don=E2=80=99t build a bank branch just to attract=C2=A0<em>overnig=
ht=C2=A0</em>funding; a branch suggests that you expect deposits to stick a=
round.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s just that=C2=A0<em>in the US regi=
onal banking mini-crisis of 2023</em>, Theory 1 completely dominates. =E2=
=80=9CWe have built long-term relationships with our depositors so we expec=
t them to stick around even as rates rise=E2=80=9D: wrong! =E2=80=9CWe hold=
 our bonds to maturity, so changes in their mark-to-market value don=E2=80=
=99t matter=E2=80=9D: wrong! =E2=80=9CActually rising interest rates are go=
od for us=E2=80=9D: wrong! And the bankers and bank regulators, who sort of=
 had Theory 2 rattling around in their brains, were taken by surprise.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Consider the collapse of Silicon Valley Bank. =
On Theory 1, this collapse is incredibly simple:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">SVB took a lot of short-term deposits=
 from venture capitalists and tech firms, and invested the money mostly in =
long-term US government bonds.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Whe=
n the Federal Reserve rapidly raised interest rates, the market value of th=
ose bonds fell.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">SVB=E2=80=99s loss=
es on those bonds came close to, and at some=C2=A0points exceeded, the valu=
e of its equity: If SVB had to sell all its bonds and pay back all its depo=
sitors, there wouldn=E2=80=99t be enough money left. It was, on a mark-to-m=
arket basis, insolvent.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People not=
iced this, and SVB=E2=80=99s unusually well-informed and connected deposito=
rs all rapidly asked for their money back.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">There wasn=E2=80=99t enough money, the bank failed, it was seized =
by the government, depositors got their money back but the government lost =
billions of dollars because SVB=E2=80=99s assets were worth much less than =
its deposits.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This story is almost <em>too=C2=A0</em>simple.=
 When you write it like that it sounds dumb. None of this is arcane or unpr=
edictable stuff. The Fed said it was going to raise interest rates a lot, a=
nd then it did. Long-term bond prices are sensitive to interest rates, so e=
veryone knew that they would fall when the Fed raised rates, and they did. =
It was pretty easy to calculate that this would make SVB insolvent, and it =
did, and then SVB put out financial statements saying =E2=80=94=C2=A0deep i=
n the footnotes, but still =E2=80=94=C2=A0that it was insolvent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But on Theory 2, SVB looked better. It had inv=
ested in building strong relationships with those VCs and tech firms, and i=
t figured that made its business extra sticky. Those VCs loved SVB; it gave=
 them (and their portfolio companies) loans that no one else did, and under=
stood their businesses better than everyone else. (Also a lot of startups g=
ot loans from SVB that=C2=A0<em>required=C2=A0</em>them to keep their cash =
on deposit at SVB, which helps with stickiness.) And, sure, rates went up a=
nd SVB=E2=80=99s bond portfolio went down and it was=C2=A0<em>technically <=
/em>a little insolvent, but that doesn=E2=80=99t matter as long as its depo=
sits stick around. SVB=E2=80=99s depositors were busy running their tech bu=
sinesses and enjoying SVB=E2=80=99s great customer service; why would they =
bother reading the footnotes to its financial statements and noticing it wa=
s insolvent? Why would they care if they did?<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week the Fed <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31378235.260432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlc2=
VydmUuZ292L25ld3NldmVudHMvcHJlc3NyZWxlYXNlcy9iY3JlZzIwMjMwNDI4YS5odG0/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBff8eb724" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> released</a> its =E2=80=9C<a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31378235.260432/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlc2VydmUuZ292L3B1YmxpY2F0aW9ucy9maWxlcy9zdmItcmV2aWV3LTIwMjM=
wNDI4LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB01540843" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Review of the Federa=
l Reserve=E2=80=99s Supervision and Regulation of Silicon Valley Bank</a>,=
=E2=80=9D picking over the failings of SVB=E2=80=99s management and the Fed=
=E2=80=99s supervision, and proposing some changes to regulation and superv=
ision to prevent this from happening again.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0I mostly want to talk about the section on interest-rate risk. It=
 describes two ways that banks measure interest-rate risk (=E2=80=9CIRR=E2=
=80=9D):=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Earnings at risk (EaR) or net interest=
 income (NII) at risk: </strong>This is an IRR metric that captures short-t=
erm exposure to interest rate movements. It measures NII volatility general=
ly over a oneyear horizon based on yield curve shocks. For example, firms w=
ill shock interest rates by 100,=C2=A0200, or more basis points (bps) in ei=
ther direction then estimate the impact to NII. A variety of different yiel=
d curve shocks and twists can be used for this exercise. Deposit assumption=
s are important for this analysis as firms must assume the amount of the ma=
rket rate movement they will pass through to deposit accounts (also known a=
s =E2=80=9Cdeposit betas=E2=80=9D).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Economic value of equity (EVE): </stro=
ng>This is an IRR metric that estimates the structural mismatches of a bank=
 balance sheet relative to yield curve movements. It is often viewed as a l=
onger-term measure as it is a discounted cash flow approach that estimates =
the present value (PV) of balance sheet cashflows to estimate economic equi=
ty (PV of assets =E2=80=93 PV of liabilities =3D economic value of equity).=
 The IRR portion of this exercise comes from shocking interest rates by var=
ious amounts (e.g., +/=E2=88=92 100, 200, or more bps) to estimate exposure=
s as cashflow paths change. Deposit assumptions are important in this exerc=
ise, so cashflows must be estimated based on customer characteristics.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notice how this works. The model is not =E2=80=
=9Cif interest rates go up by 100 basis points, our assets will lose X% of =
their value, which seems bad.=E2=80=9D Instead it is =E2=80=9Cif interest r=
ates go up by 100 basis points, our cash flows from our assets will go up b=
y $Y, and our interest expense on deposits will go up by $Z=E2=80=9D: Impli=
citly, the model treats both the assets and the deposits as long-term and o=
nly partially rates-sensitive.=C2=A0If Y is greater than Z, then it is=C2=
=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>for interest rates to go up. And Z =E2=80=94=C2=A0how=
 much more the bank will have to pay on deposits if interest rates go up =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0is very much an estimate.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB=E2=80=99s estimates were bad:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVBFG=E2=80=99s IRR results showed that there =
was a mismatch between the repricing of assets and liabilities on the bank=
=E2=80=99s balance sheet. The results showed that SVBFG had historically be=
en=C2=A0asset sensitive, which means that NII increased as rates increased.=
 This was due to the nature of SVBFG=E2=80=99s balance sheet that had consi=
sted of predominantly non-interest-bearing deposits on the liability side a=
nd a mix of floating rate loans and fixed rate securities on the asset side=
. SVBFG expected to benefit in a rising rate environment, as it generally a=
ssumed that deposit betas would be low.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In response to EVE breaches, SVBFG made model =
changes that reduced the level of risk depicted by the model. In similar fa=
shion to the response to liquidity shortfalls, management changed assumptio=
ns rather than the balance sheet to alter reported risks. In April=C2=A0202=
2, SVBFG made a poorly supported change in assumption to increase the durat=
ion of its deposits based on a deposit study conducted by a consultant and =
in-house analysis.95 Under the internal models in use, the change reduced t=
he mismatch of durations between assets and liabilities and gave the appear=
ance of reduced IRR; however, no risk had been taken off the balance sheet.=
 The assumptions were unsubstantiated given recent deposit growth, lack of =
historical data, rapid increases in rates that shorten deposit duration, an=
d the uniqueness of SVBFG=E2=80=99s client base.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And it made bad choices:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In early 2022, at a time when rate=
s were rising rapidly, SVBFG became increasingly concerned with decreasing =
NII if rates were to decrease, rather than with the impact of rates continu=
ing to increase. This was based on observed yield curve inversion that coul=
d be an indication of an impending recession and a subsequent decrease in r=
ates. The bank began positioning its balance sheet to protect NII against f=
alling interest rates but not rising ones. SVBFG was very focused on NII an=
d profits and the NII sensitivity metrics were showing that NII was exposed=
 to falling rates. Rising rates were seen as an opportunity to take profits=
 on hedges, and the bank began a strategy to remove hedges in March 2022, w=
hich were designed to protect NII in rising rate scenarios but also would h=
ave served to constrain NII if rates were to decrease.=C2=A0</p></blockquot=
e>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so you can read <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31378235.260432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9p=
eD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMDAwMDcxOTczOS8wMDAwNzE5NzM5MjMwMDAwMjE=
vc2l2Yi0yMDIyMTIzMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB648b78bf" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> SVB=E2=
=80=99s annual report for 2022</a>. On pages 89-90, SVB reports its analysi=
s of interest-rate risk, which shows that SVB=E2=80=99s net interest income=
 will go=C2=A0<em>up=C2=A0</em>if rates go up: Rising rates will be good fo=
r SVB, said SVB. Meanwhile page 164, in Note 22 to the financial statements=
, is where SVB reports the $15 billion of interest-rate-driven mark-to-mark=
et losses on its held-to-maturity bonds that left it nearly insolvent and t=
hat would be its undoing: Rising rates were in fact very very bad for SVB. =
But those mark-to-market losses were just=C2=A0<em>not a factor=C2=A0</em>i=
n its interest-rate risk analysis! Didn=E2=80=99t come up! Didn=E2=80=99t s=
eem relevant!=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just the purest Theory 2 stuff: Deposits are s=
ticky, mark-to-market values of assets are irrelevant, and rising rates are=
 good for the bank. The Fed=C2=A0supervisors pushed back on this a bit=C2=
=A0at the time, but not very much:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A review of the supervisory record shows that =
Federal Reserve supervisors identified some but not all of the interest rat=
e risk-management issues that contributed to the failure of SVBFG. Supervis=
ory responses for IRR were not rapid or severe enough given the fundamental=
 issues in this area that actually drove poor decisions at SVBFG. =E2=80=A6=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Limit breaches with respect to the EVE metric =
were evident in the 2020, 2021, and 2022 CAMELS exams. In the 2020 CAMELS e=
xam, the examiner proposed an advisory on the lack of escalation, monitorin=
g, and taking actions to remediate breaches. Additionally, in several CAMEL=
S exams (2020, 2021), examiners identified issues related to lack of sensit=
ivity testing,=C2=A0back-testing, gaps with policies, ineffective control f=
unctions, and lack of oversight from senior management and the board of dir=
ectors. During the 2021 CAMELS exam, the examiner proposed an observation r=
elated to lack of sensitivity testing of key assumptions.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CLack of sensitivity testing of key as=
sumptions,=E2=80=9D fine. But nobody said the dumb simple thing of =E2=80=
=9Chey if interest rates go up all your fixed-rate bonds will lose value an=
d your balance sheet will look insolvent and=C2=A0people will get nervous.=
=E2=80=9D The dead simple thing that brought SVB down, the thing that every=
one knows and that seems obvious in retrospect, the simple Theory 1 story t=
hat rising interest rates are bad for a bank with a lot of long-term fixed-=
rate assets, is not really how banks or bank examiners think. They think ab=
out banks as having long-term assets but also long-term liabilities, so the=
 effect of rising rates is complex and unpredictable.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think this is the basic explanation for how =
rapid and serious and=C2=A0<em>surprising=C2=A0</em>this banking crisis is.=
 Banks and regulators have historically operated in large part in Theory 2,=
 treating bank funding as pretty long-term and trying to match banks=E2=80=
=99 assets to that effectively long-term funding. And in spring 2023 that j=
ust doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0work at all.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why? I don=E2=80=99t know. Some speculations<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This is the first large rapid interes=
t-rate hiking cycle in a long time, and so Theory 2 hadn=E2=80=99t been=C2=
=A0<em>tested=C2=A0</em>in a while. And things have changed since it was la=
st tested.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Like the internet? It i=
s much easier to move your money out of a 0%-interest bank account and into=
 a 5%-interest money-market account (or an online high-yield savings accoun=
t, etc.) than it was 30 years ago, or even 10 years ago. You are more likel=
y to see an online ad encouraging you to do that, and more likely to do it =
with a few clicks.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Similarly, more=
 information is available online, and more people are in the business of cu=
rating it for you and emphasizing the juicy bits. So if your bank has huge =
mark-to-market losses, you are more likely to hear about it. And if you are=
 worried about the solvency of your bank, you can tweet or Whatsapp or grou=
p-text about it, and worries can spread faster, and you can withdraw your m=
oney via app. =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/31378235.260432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjMtMDQtMTMvdHdpdHRlci1nZXRzLWludG8tdGhlLXN0b2NrLWJ1c2luZXNzP2NtcGlkP=
UJCRDA1MDQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0=
dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUwNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB8a32080e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">Game=E2=80=99s the same, just got more fierce</a=
>,=E2=80=9D is the diagnosis of the vice chairman of the Federal Deposit In=
surance Corp.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also, though, the wo=
rld has become more financialized, and specifically more=C2=A0<em>mark-to-m=
arket</em>. Thirty years ago you could say =E2=80=9Cwell we are a bank, it =
doesn=E2=80=99t matter if the market value of our securities goes down, as =
long as we don=E2=80=99t have to sell them,=E2=80=9D and that was sort of a=
 coherent. Now it sounds crazy; it sounds like fraud. Mark-to-market discip=
line has taken over the financial world, and to the extent that banking is =
about the opposite =E2=80=94=C2=A0about=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>marking asse=
ts to market =E2=80=94=C2=A0it has a hard time.<a class=3D"footnote-index" =
href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: =
inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The 2008 financial crisis involve=
d a lot of businesses =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cshadow banks=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that borrowed short to lend long and sort of figured that their sh=
ort-term funding was actually pretty stable and long-term. That worked out =
poorly, and people are skeptical about similar claims even from actual bank=
s with branches and everything.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Re=
lationship businesses in general are on the decline. In a world of electron=
ic communication and global supply chains and work-from-home and the gig ec=
onomy, business relationships are less sticky and =E2=80=9CI am going to go=
 into my bank branch and shake the hand of the manager and trust her with m=
y life savings=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t work. =E2=80=9CI am going to do stu=
ff for relationship reasons, even if it costs me 0.5% of interest income, o=
r a slightly=C2=A0increased risk of losing my money=E2=80=9D is no longer a=
 plausible thing to think. Silicon Valley Bank=E2=80=99s VC and tech custom=
ers talked lovingly about how good their relationships with SVB were, after=
 withdrawing all their money. They=C2=A0had fiduciary duties to their own i=
nvestors to keep their money safe! Relationships didn=E2=80=99t matter.</li=
>
</ol>
