<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or just, like, you are a regional bank, your a=
ssets have lost value, you look a little bit mark-to-market insolvent, what=
 do you do? Well, the traditional approach is that you raise equity: You se=
ll stock to investors, so that you will have more equity, so that you will =
no longer be insolvent. Why would the investors buy the stock? Well, the tr=
aditional answer is that a bank is worth more than just its balance sheet, =
more than its assets minus its liabilities. It has those relationships! It =
can generate income in the future, which is worth something, even if its as=
sets have technically lost value.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[8]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it turns out that if you are a troubled re=
gional bank and you go out to raise equity in the spring of 2023, investors=
 will say =E2=80=9Chmm it says here that your assets are worth less than yo=
ur liabilities,=E2=80=9D they will not buy the stock, and your depositors w=
ill also notice and panic and flee. It is tempting to sit very still and ho=
pe no one notices; raising equity is too risky.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31378235.260432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDQvdXMtcmV2aWV3cy1nb2xkbWFuLXJvbGU=
td2l0aC1zaWxpY29uLXZhbGxleS1iYW5rLWJlZm9yZS1jb2xsYXBzZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTA0Mj=
NfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fd=
GVybT0yMzA1MDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB86f=
e4c1f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">Anyway</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman Sachs Group Inc.=E2=80=99s role in Sil=
icon Valley Bank=E2=80=99s attempt to raise funds in March is under review =
by US governmental agencies, which are looking into the failed transaction =
that helped push the US regional-banking system into turmoil.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Wall Street titan is cooperating and provi=
ding information to the government in connection with their investigations =
and inquiries into Silicon Valley bank, including the role the firm played =
with the now-failed bank in March, according to a regulatory filing.=C2=A0<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB offloaded a $24 billion portfolio to Goldm=
an at a loss and sought the firm=E2=80=99s help in raising more than $2.2 b=
illion to cover the shortfall, according to disclosures in March. Goldman c=
ouldn=E2=80=99t pull off the deal and a bank run in the wake of that offeri=
ng effectively doomed SVB. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On March 8, Goldman pitched a plan to investor=
s to help plug [SVB=E2=80=99s capital] hole, and then some, by raising $2.2=
5 billion in capital from General Atlantic and other investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rival banks and investors have privately and p=
ublicly pointed fingers at Goldman for failing to line up the capital in ad=
vance and spooking the market. In the bankers=E2=80=99 view, they were raci=
ng the clock to defuse the Moody=E2=80=99s threat [of a ratings downgrade].=
 That didn=E2=80=99t leave them enough time to canvass the market, line up =
the funding and present a neatly put-together deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB=E2=80=99s customers raced to pull their de=
posits from the bank, concerned about its health. On March 9, customers sou=
ght to yank $42 billion of deposits from SVB, or roughly a quarter of its y=
ear-end deposits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The spiraling chaos forced Goldman to shelve t=
he offering, and by the end of the week regulators had seized the Californi=
a firm, which at the time was the second-biggest bank failure in US history=
.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I assume the investigation is less about =E2=
=80=9Cdid you mess up the capital raise=E2=80=9D and more about =E2=80=9Cdi=
d you buy the bond portfolio at a price that was good for you and made the =
capital situation worse,=E2=80=9D but the capital raise did not help.=C2=A0=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/31378235.260432/aHR0cHM6Ly9kb2NzLmdvb2dsZS5jb20vZG9jd=
W1lbnQvZC8xMWFKRlVtMFFON0lza0JidTIzVGtZa3psYmZuWUo5N0Zlb2doOWpGSXo0QS9lZGl0=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB04405ac6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here is a proposal</a> for =E2=
=80=9CResolving the Banking Crisis=E2=80=9D by=C2=A0Peter DeMarzo, Erica Ji=
ang, Arvind Krishnamurthy,=C2=A0Gregor Matvos, Tomasz Piskorski and Amit Se=
ru. Their basic argument is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A ton of banks have big mark-to-marke=
t losses due to interest-rate moves: They estimate that =E2=80=9C2,315 bank=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0accounting for $11 trillion of assets in aggregate =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0fall below=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>zero=C2=A0</em>equity if their assets=
 are marked to market.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But =E2=80=
=9Cthe mark-to-market test =E2=80=A6 is a component of solvency, but is not=
 determinant.=C2=A0Banks have franchise value that is not reflected in the =
value of the securities and loans they own. Thus it is likely that a large =
fraction of the 2,315 banks in the figure are solvent on a long-term basis =
even after the interest rate shock we have experienced.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So the Fed should force them to raise equity=
: =E2=80=9CEconomic solvency requires a market test. The ability to raise n=
ew equity or long-term unsecured debt from outside investors is a market te=
st that draws a clean line between solvent but illiquid and insolvent. In a=
ddition, new capital inflows will reduce fragility and restore =E2=80=98ski=
n in the game=E2=80=99 for these institutions.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Maybe! But the recent experience is that tryin=
g to raise equity can=C2=A0<em>cause=C2=A0</em>the collapse: If you need to=
 raise money, nobody wants to hear about =E2=80=9Cfranchise value.=E2=80=9D=
 This is a problem, because DeMarzo et al. are not wrong: Most of these ban=
ks probably are economically viable, and the solution to a banking crisis r=
eally is to raise more equity. But it seems to be a bit stuck.</p>
