a23cB513a4604" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">  wrote yesterday</a> about the US Securities and Ex=
change Commission=E2=80=99s theory of stock buybacks. In particular, there =
is sort of a background theory of =E2=80=9Cbuybacks are bad because compani=
es should be spending that money on salaries or research instead,=E2=80=9D =
but the SEC=E2=80=99s concern is the more niche theory that =E2=80=9Cbuybac=
ks are bad because executives sell stock when companies are buying.=E2=80=
=9D I quoted a 2018 speech by former SEC Commissioner Robert Jackson:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In half of the buybacks we studied=
, at least one executive sold shares in the month following the buyback ann=
ouncement. In fact, twice as many companies have insiders selling in the ei=
ght days after a buyback announcement as sell on an ordinary day. So right =
after the company tells the market that the stock is cheap, executives over=
whelmingly decide to sell.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Like three people emailed me to say: Well, of =
course. Most of the time, companies announce a buyback when they announce q=
uarterly earnings. And most public companies have =E2=80=9Cblackout periods=
,=E2=80=9D in which executives are not allowed to trade stock for some port=
ion of each quarter (when they might have nonpublic information about earni=
ngs), but=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>allowed to sell stock in the =E2=80=9Copen=
 window=E2=80=9D shortly after the company announces earnings (because then=
 all of the information is public). If executives can only trade on 30 days=
 each quarter, and those 30 days are the ones right after an earnings annou=
ncement, then executives will naturally concentrate their trading in the ti=
mes after buyback announcements. But it is not=C2=A0<em>because of the buyb=
ack</em>; it is because of how public-company calendars work.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway though the SEC does seem keen on this t=
heory, and the new rules it adopted yesterday include that each public comp=
any will have to disclose =E2=80=9Cany policies and procedures relating to =
purchases and sales of the issuer=E2=80=99s securities during a repurchase =
program by its officers and directors, including any restriction on such tr=
ansactions.=E2=80=9D I pointed out that this is a soft way for the SEC to s=
ay =E2=80=9Ccompanies=C2=A0<em>should=C2=A0</em>restrict executives from tr=
ading stock during a buyback.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Combine that with the open-window point, and y=
ou get something like the following:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Executives can only trade in a short =
window after earnings.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The SEC wan=
ts to ban them from trading during a stock buyback.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">If a company does a buyback, it=E2=80=99s going to be in =
the short window after earnings.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Therefore, if a company does buyb=
acks regularly, its executives will pretty much never be able to trade stoc=
k.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Therefore executives will have =
to stop selling stock, or companies will have to stop doing buybacks.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Feels like the sort of result the SEC might li=
ke.</p>
